✅ 1. Requirement Understanding (MOST IMPORTANT)

Before writing even 1 line of code:
Understand application functionality
Identify critical user flows
Clarify:
What needs automation?
What should NOT be automated?

✅ 2. Feasibility Analysis

Not everything is automatable.
Check:
Stable UI?
Unique locators available?
Any 3rd-party restrictions?
Frequent UI changes?
👉 Example:
Static forms → Good candidate
Drag-drop with canvas → Hard (needs advanced handling)
✅ 3. Define Automation Scope

Decide clearly:
Smoke tests
Regression suite
Critical business flows
API vs UI split

👉 Real-time:

70% API automation (fast & stable)
30% UI automation (critical paths)

✅ 4. Tool & Technology Selection

Based on project needs:
UI Automation
Selenium WebDriver
Appium
Test Framework
TestNG
Build Tool
Maven
API Testing
Postman / RestAssured

👉 Selection depends on:

Team skillset
Application type (web/mobile/API)

✅ 5. Framework Design (VERY IMPORTANT FOR 7–8 YEARS)

You must decide architecture:

Page Object Model (POM)
Data-Driven Framework
Hybrid Framework

👉 Typical structure:

src/test/java
  ├── pages
  ├── tests
  ├── utils
  ├── base
  └── resources

👉 Include:

Reusable methods
Common utilities (waits, screenshots, logs)
✅ 6. Test Data Strategy

Decide:

Static vs Dynamic data
External files:
Excel
JSON
DB

👉 Example:

Login → multiple users (valid/invalid)
Use parameterization (TestNG DataProvider)
✅ 7. Environment Setup

You need:

Dev / QA / UAT environments
Stable test URL
Test accounts
DB access (if needed)

👉 Real issue:

Automation fails if environment is unstable, not script issue
✅ 8. Locator Strategy

Very critical for stability:

Use priority:

ID
Name
CSS
XPath (last option)

👉 Avoid:

Dynamic XPath
Index-based locators
✅ 9. Version Control Setup

Use:

Git
GitHub

Setup:

Repo creation
Branch strategy (main, qa, feature)
✅ 10. CI/CD Integration

Automation should not run manually.

Use:

Jenkins

👉 Setup:

Scheduled runs
Trigger on build
Generate reports
✅ 11. Reporting Mechanism

Need clear reports:

Extent Reports / Allure
Pass/Fail logs
Screenshots for failures
✅ 12. Logging & Debugging

Use logs for debugging:

Log4j / SLF4J
Capture:
Steps executed
Failures
✅ 13. Exception Handling & Wait Strategy

Avoid flaky tests:

Use Explicit Waits (NOT Thread.sleep)
Handle:
Stale elements
Timeouts
✅ 14. Coding Standards & Best Practices

Define rules:

Naming conventions
Reusable methods
No hardcoding
Clean code
✅ 15. Team Readiness

Ensure:

Team knows tools
Basic Java knowledge
Framework understanding
🔥 Real-Time Interview Answer (Short Version)

If interviewer asks:

👉 “What are prerequisites before starting automation?”

You can say:

Before starting automation, I ensure requirement clarity, feasibility analysis, and define automation scope. Then I finalize tools like Selenium, TestNG, and Maven based on project needs. I design a scalable framework using Page Object Model, set up test data strategy, environment readiness, and stable locator strategy. I also integrate Git for version control and Jenkins for CI/CD, along with reporting and logging mechanisms to ensure maintainability and reliability.
